  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a **felony** in most jurisdictions, including the United States. It is a serious criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The purpose of money laundering is to make the funds appear as if they come from a legitimate source.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is punishable under federal law (e.g., the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**) and can also be prosecuted under state laws. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- **Prison sentences**: Up to 20 years or more, depending on the severity of the crime.\n- **Fines**: Significant financial penalties, often amounting to hundreds of thousands or millions of dollars.\n- **Forfeiture of assets**: The government can seize assets involved in or obtained through money laundering.\n\nMoney laundering is often associated with other crimes, such as drug trafficking, fraud, terrorism financing, or organized crime, which can lead to additional charges and harsher penalties.\n\nIf you are facing allegations of money laundering, it is critical to consult with a qualified attorney to understand your legal rights and options.",
